StringLiteralExpr.value: \bfNatural and Step Response of RLC Circuits
The application of KCL to the parallel RLC circuit and KVL to the series RLC circuit will result
in the following linear time-invariant second-order differential equations.
The {\bf characteristic equation} for both the parallel and series RLC circuits is given by
s^2 + 2 \alpha s + {\omega_0}^2 = 0, where \alpha is the damping factor and \omega_0 is the undamped natural frequency.
For a parallel circuit \alpha = 1/(2RC), for a series circuit \alpha = R/(2L) and for both cases \omega_0 = 1/(LC)^{1/2}.
The roots of the characteristic equations are: s_{1,2} = -\alpha \pm (\alpha^2 - {\omega_0}^2)^{1/2}
The form of response depends on the values of \alpha and \omega_0.
1. \alpha > \omega_0 (real distinct roots), response is overdamped: x(t) = x_f + A_1 e^{s_1t} + A_2 e^{s_2t}
2. \alpha < \omega_0 (complex roots), underdamped: x(t) = x_f + e^{-\alpha t}(B_1 cos \omega_d t + B_2 sin \omega_d t)
3. \alpha = \omega_0 (equal roots), critically damped: x(t) = x_f + e^{-\alpha t}(D_1 t + D_2)
The above constants are obtained from the initial conditions, x(0^+) and dx(0^+)/dt.
This program obtains the natural and step response of parallel and series RLC circuits. After selecting
one of the push buttons below, you can specify the step input, circuit parameters and initial values.
The Solve buttons are then pressed to obtain the analytical response and plots of currents or voltages.
